<TITLE> World Bank okays $23.6m loan </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 6 (bdnews24.com)  The World Bank has approved $23.6 million in loans for Bangladesh to improve public procurement system, the bank said in a statement Thursday. The bank's concessionary arm International Development Association will mobilise the fund to help improve procurement quality through better management and monitoring. The public procurement reform project aims to strengthen procurement management at sectoral level and create a sustained programme of developing skilled procurement professionals. It is also designed to introduce electronic government procurement in target agencies and the Central Procurement Technical Unit on a pilot basis. The project will target four agencies of key sectoral ministries (target agencies) chosen for the size of their annual procurement spending: Roads and Highways Department, Local Government Engineering Department, and Rural Electrification Board, and Bangladesh Water Development Board. This project builds on the first Public Procurement Reform Project, which was approved by the World Bank on May 2, 2002. The loan is interest free and has 40 years to maturity with a 10-year grace period; it carries a service charge of 0.75 percent, the report said. bd
